{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_2hayden_ver02/data/sn83045462/0028060530A/1949030201/0718.xml":{"full_text":"Weather Forecast\nMostly sunny, high in mid 40s today. Fair\ntonight, low near 28 in city, 22 in suburbs.\nTomorrow partly cloudy, high in up\nper 40s. (Full report on Page A-2.1\nMidnight, 30 6 a.m. ___27 11 a.m. --34\n2 a.m. 29 8 a.m._29 Noon-36\n4 a.m. .-.28 10 a.m. ...33 1 p.m. _.-39\nLote New York Markets, Page A-25\nGuide for Readers\nAmuse\u2019ts __A-20-21\nComics _B-18-19\nEditorial _A-12\nEdit'l Articles.A-13\nFinance _A-25\nLost and Found A-3\nPate\nObituary .A-14\nRadio _B-19\nSociety, Clubs B-3\nSports _A-22-23\nWhere to Go_-B-10\nWoman's Page.B-12\nAn Associated Press Newspaper\n97th Year. No. 60. Phone ST. 5000\nWASHINGTON, D. C\u201e WEDNESDAY, MARCH 2, 1949-FOBTY-SIX PAGES.\nCity Home Delivery. Dally and Sunday. $1.20 a Month. When 6 gj /''\u2019\u2022Tp'VT\u2019CI\nSundays, $1.80. Nlyht Pinal Edition. $1.30 and $1.40 per Month J\nB-50 MAKES FIRST NON-STOP WORLD FLIGHT\nHouse Approval\nOf D. C. Budget\nExpected Today\nChurch Takes Floor\nTo Urge Increase\nIn Federal Payment\nBy Don S. Warren\nThe House today took up the\nDistrict's somewhat reduced but\nstill unbalanced appropriation bill\nfor the year beginning July 1 with\nprospects that it would be passed\nby mid-afternoon and sent to the\nSenate.\nAs the bill was reported from\nthe Appropriations Committee, it\ncalls for an outlay of $98,923,621,\nor $4,399,880 less than the record\nbreaking budget submitted by the\u2019j\nCommissioners.\nEven with the cuts, however, the\nHouse was told by Representative\nBates of Kentucky, chairman of\nthe District Subcommittee of the\nHouse Appropriations Committee,\nthat the bill leaves a prospective\ndeficit of $2,534,000.\n15fr Increase Recommended.\nMr. Bates told the House the\nCommissioners are required by law\nto increase the tax on real estate\nand tangible personal property\nto prevent a deficit. A 15-cent\nincrease in the present $2 rate on\neach $100 of value, he said, would\ncover the deficit.\nThe cuts were made, the sub\ncommittee chairman said, because\nof the \"serious financial condition\u201d\nfacing the city. Some of the cuts,\nhe added, were based on the\nbelief of the subcommittee that\neconomies could be made.\nRepresentative Church, Repub\nlican, of Illinois, ranking minority\nmember of the subcommittee in\ncharge of the city supply bill, took\nthe floor to call for a larger and\n\"fairer\u201d Federal payment toward\nDistrict expenses and for passage\nof the proposed 2 per cent city\nsales tax. The present Federal\npayment is $11,000,000 for the gen\neral fund plus $1,000,000 ear\nmarked as payment for District\nwater service to Federal buildings.\nNew Bill\u2019s Provisions.\nThe new revenue bill being j\ndrafted by subcommittees of the\nHouse and Senate District Com\nmittees proposed a temporary\n$4,000,000 increase in the Federal\npayment as well as a sales tax,\ndoubling of liquor taxes and re\nvision of the city income levy.\nJust before the House met, Rep\nresentative Smith, Democrat, of\nVirginia, chairman of the fiscal\nsubcommittee of the House Dis\ntrict Committee, declared the pro\nposed cuts in the budget in no\nway removed the need for in\ncreased city revenues.\nAbout all the appropriations\ncommittee accomplished in slic\ning nearly $4,400,000 from the\ncity supply bill, he said, was to\npostpone to next year some of the\ncity\u2019s appropriation needs.\nIt should be remembered, Mr.\nSmith said, that passage of pend\ning proposals to give District em\nployes the pay raise already\nawarded Federal workers, would\nadd at least $10,000,000 to the\ncity\u2019s prospective deficit.\nSmith Backs Pay Raise.\nLike most members of Congress\nwho have studied the question,\nhe believes Congress will grant\nthe pay raise to city workers.\n\"It is only a matter of com\nmon justice that they be given\nthe cost-of-living pay raise,\u2019\u2019 Mr.\nSmith said.\nWhile the reductions in the\nappropriations bill proposed by the\nAppropriations Committee would\nreduce the anticipated deficit tc\nabout $2,500,000, Mr. Smith said\nhe expected that most of the items\neliminated would be restoied by\nthe Senate.\nMr. Bates, who is in charge of\nthe appropriation measure, said\ni7See BUDGETrPage A-6.) i\nDeaths in High Winds\nRise to 30 in Europe\nBy th\u00ab Associated Press\nLONDON, Mar. 2.\u2014The March\nwind blew into Europe yesterday,\nsnuffed out at least 30 lives and\ncaused property damage running\ninto the millions.\nGusts up to 90 miles an hour\nfar above hurricane force\u2014pushed\nover buildings, sank ships and\nflooded coasts.\nTwenty-six persons were killed\nIn the collapse of war-damaged\nbuildings in Western Germany. A\nman died under a toppled wall in\nRome. Another, inspecting gale\ndamage to a roof in England, was\nblown off and killed. A British\nwoman was killed by a falling\nchimney just a few hours before\nher baby was due. In Genoa a\nsailor was killed by a toppling\nmast.\nThe Polish steamer Katowice\nsank in the North Sea. The Brit\nish coaler Marena sank in the\nharbor of Banff, Scotland\n\u2022Aircraft were grounded, the Ber\nlin airlift stopped for several\nhours. Electricity was cut off in\nparts of Southern Italy and tele\nphone service In parts of England.\nBulgaria Cancels\nTestimony of 42\nIn Church Trial\n'Evidence Abundant/\nProsecutor Says in\nHalting Witnesses\nBy Richard Kasischke\nAssociated Press Foreign Correspondent\nSOFIA, Bulgaria, Mar. 2.\u2014The\nprosecution in Bulgaria's trial of\n15 Protestant pastors accused of,\nspying for the United States and\nBritain today suddenly canceled\nthe scheduled appearances of 42\nof its witnesses.\nThe prosecution said the evi\ndence is abundant and clear. We\nneed not hear any more.'\u2019\nThe government had intended\nto present 53 witnesses against\nthe defendants, all of whom\nsigned confessions while they were\nheld secretly for three months by\nthe Communist security police.\nThe cancellation of the remain\ning1. testimony came after the\ncourt had heard a dragging parade\nof witnesses who sought to prove\nthat the pastors were spying for\nthe United States and Britain.\nThe testimony hammered at\nthe United States and American\nchurch missions. Apparently the\ngovernment intended to incrimi-1\nnate any Bulgarian sect which\nhad ties with Weslern church\nheadquarters and to sever those\nties. The prosecution appeared\nto be trying to show that funds!\nsent by American missions to Bul\ngarian churches were not church\naid but pay for espionage. The\ndefendants also are accused of\nblack market money transactions.\nThe cutting of Bulgarian\nchurch relations with the West;\nTContinued on Page A-6, Col. 6.)\nU. S. Blockades Reds\nRefusing to Depart\nFrom American Zone\nFood and Utilities Cut\nOff From Repatriation\nMission in Germany\n(Picture on Page A-6J\nBy th\u00ab Associated Pres*\nFRANKFURT, Germany, Mar.\n2.\u2014Armed military police to^ay\nblockaded a Russian mission which\nrefused American orders to leave\nthe American zone of Germany.\nSupplies of water, gas and elec\ntrcity were cut off and telephones\ndisconnected in the bloodless siege\nof the Russian repatriation mis\nsion here. Food was shut off by\noiders of MPs to arrest any one\ntrying to enter the building or\nleave it.\nFour officiers and four soldiers\nand their families are in the mis\nsion. No one knew how much\nfood they had.\nRussian Officer Turned Away.\nA Russian officer, apparently\nfrom the Soviet military mission,\ntried to enter the house, but was\nturned away by an MP.\nThe mission handled the return\nof displaced persons to Russia.\nThree hours after the siege be\ngan, a German employe and his\nwife left the mission. They pushed\na bicycle loaded with two boxes\nand a blanket roll.\n\u201cWe are not coming back,\" said\nthe German. The couple was es\ncorted to a military police sta\ntion for questioning.\nGen. Lucius D. Clay, American\nmilitary governor, February 16\nasked the mission to leave by\nMarch 1 because the number of\nDPs now agreeing to return to\nRussian is negligible. He said the\nregular Russian military mission\ncould handle the work, and lifted\nthe credentials of the repatriation\nmission.\nViolation of Pacts Charged.\nThe Russians protested vehe\nmently and denounced the order\nas a violation of the Yalta and\nPotsdam agreements.\nThe United States Army set a\ndeadline of last midnight for the\nRussians to leave. But forceful\nmeasures were not planned.\nGen. Clay said \u201cas long as they\ndon\u2019t want to get out of the house,\nwe are in no hurry about getting\nthem out.\u201d\nThe Russians remained in the\nhouse and at midnight the big\nyellow building was a blaze of\nlight.\nAt about 8 a.m. this morning (21\na.m., EST), a platoon of American\nmilitary police headed by Col.\nSterling Wood, Frankfurt provost\nmarshal, left American post head\n(Continued on Page A-6. Col. 2.)\nMarshall Petain Weaker\nDue to Age, Doctors Say\nBy th\u00ab Ai\u00abociat\u00bbd Pr\u00ab\u00bb\u00ab\nPARIS, Mar. 2.\u2014The health of'\nMarshal Henri Phillipe Petain is'\n\u201cshowing a gradual weakening due j\nto old age,\u201d three physicians told\nthe French cabinet today.\nThere'is \u201cno particular malady\u201d\nto which Marshal Petain\u2019s loss of\nhealth can be attributed, the med\nical report stated.\nThe doctors were sent by the\nstate to the lie d\u2019Yeu where the\nhead of France's Vichy govern\nment is imprisoned. The marshal\nwill be 93 on April 24.\nHoover Board\nFinds Serious\nDefects in VA\nUrges Separation of\nInsurance Operations\nFrom Other Functions\nBy Francis P. Douglas\nThe Hoover Commission recom\nmended to Congress today that\nthe Veterans\u2019 Administration's in\nsurance operations be separated\nfrom all other VA programs and\norganized as a Government cor\nporation.\nIt recommended also that the\nveterans' housing loan g-uarantee\nprogram be transferred to the\nHousing and Home Finance\nAgency.\nSerious defects still exist in the\norganization of the huge veterans'\nagency, the commission asserted.\nIt said the entire structure has\nbecome too complicated. It urged\na thorough reorganization.\nIn handling veterans\u2019 insurance,\nthe commission said, the average\nwork load per employe is 450 in\nsuryice policies. This was con\ntrasted with the work load of\n1,762 policies per employe in a\nprivate company.\n186,000 Employes.\nIndicating the size of the agency,\nthe commission said VA has 186,\n000 employes, 11,732 of them in\nWashington; its expenditures for\nfiscal 1950 are estimated at $5,300,\n000,000, or about 11 per cent of the\nnational budget\u2014more than any\nother agency except the military\nestablishment and the Treasury.\nIn describing defects generally,\nthe commission reported there are\nconflicting lines of authority and\ndivided responsibility between\nWashington and the field offices,\ntoo many organizational units,\ntoo many staff offices for major\nprograms and such voluminous\nwritten instructions that they\ndefy intelligent execution. In\nconnection with the last statement\nthe commission cited 88 different\nmanuals. 665 varieties of technical\nbulletins and more than 400 cir\nculars.\nIn addition to the insurance\nand home loan program recom\nmendations, the commission urged\nthat:\nAdministration of pensions, re\ntirement benefits, disability com\npensation and guardianships\nshould be consolidated in a Vet\nerans' Benefit Service.\nReadjustment Proposal.\nVocational rehabitation, educa\ntion and readjustment allowance\nprograms, and the certification of\nveterans for loan guarantees\nshould be consolidated in a Re\nadjustment Service. The report\nsaid VA should set up its own\nlist of certified schools, in addi\ntion to State lists of accredited\ninstitutions, and refuse to pay\nGI tuition to any school not on\nthe lists.\nThe Office of Legislation should\nbe consolidated with that of the\nGeneral Counsel.\nThe Co-ordination Service should\nbecome an Office of Management\nResearch under an assistant ad\nministrator, and it should include\nthe present inspection and in\nvestigation research service.\nRecommendation concerning\ngeneral management were these:\nThat the Veterans\u2019 Administra\ntor reorganize his office along the\nlines recommended in the com\nmission\u2019s first report on \"General\nManagement in the Executive\nBranch.\"\nThat the executive assistant ad\nministrator become deputy ad\nministrator and that there be\nthree or more assistant admini\nstrators with functions assigned\nby the administrator.\nNinth Report by Group.\nThat all management services\nbe consolidated under an assist\nant administrator for administra\ntive services.\nThe report on \u201cVeterans\u2019 Af\nfairs\u201d is the ninth made to Con\ngress by the bipartisan Commis\nsion on Organization of the\n(See HOOVER, Page A-6.)\nPius XII Quietly Observes\n10th Anniversary as Pope\nBy th\u00ab Associated Press\nVATICAN CITY. Mar. 2.\u2014Pope\nPius XII observed the 10th an\nniversary of his elevation to the\nthrone of St. Peter today without\nany special ceremony.\nThe anniversary, which also was\nthe pontiffs 73d birthday, was\nspent in the usual arduous routine\nof the, papacy, including a long\nlist of 'audiences.\nOn March 12 there will be a\nspecial mass in the Sistine Chapel\nto celebrate the 10th anniversary\nof his coronation. On April 2 the\nPope will make a radio address on\nthe 50th anniversary of his ordina\ntion as a priest.\nHis Holiness\u2019 thin, ascetic face\nmay be more deeply lined than it\nwas 10 years ago, but his step is\nfirm and his deep-set eyes as\nbright as ever. His resistance to\nfatigue is still the marvel of his\naides.\n_____\n\nBig Bomber Is Refueled in Air 4 Times\nIn 4-Day, 23,452-Mile Trip From Texas\nThe Air Force\u2019s B-50 -\u2018Lucky Lady II\u201d touches the runway at Carswell Air Force Base at Fort Worth, Tex., completing tne nrsv\nnon-stop flight around the world. (Another photo on.Page A-3.)___~~AP Wirephoto.\nVandenberg Urges\nSenators to Decide\nFor Selves on Cloture\nG. 0. P. Leader Doesn't\nWant Loyalty to F4im\nTo Affect Decision\nBy th\u00bb Associated Press\nSenator Vandenberg, Republican,\nof Michigan said today he doesn't\nwant any personal loyalty to him\nto sway Republicans on what may\nbe a vital point in the effort to\nbreak the filibuster Southern Sen\nators are carrying on against\nchanging Senate rules.\nThe point would develop if they\nare faced with upholding or re\njecting a ruling by Vice President\nBarkley that could end the present\nSenate debate.\n\u201cI want the Republicans to vote\nthe way they think is right, with\nout any thought of whether they\nare upholding me or Barkley,\u201d the\nMichigan Senator said.\nHe added that he has no per\nsonal \u2018\u2018pride of opinion\u201d in a ruling\nhe made as the Senate's presiding\nofficer last year that a cloture\u2014or\ndebate limiting\u2014petition can't stop\nsenatorial talk about a motion.\nHe obviously still believes that\nruling is sound, however, and may\nsupport it in a talk in the Senate\nlater.\nTo File Petition Tomorrow.\nSenate Majority Leader Lucas\nhas moved to bring up a resolu\ntion by Senator Wherry of Nebras\nka, the Republican floor leader,\nand Chairman Hayden of the Sen\nate Rules Committee. It would\nchange the Senate rules so that\ntwo-thirds of those voting can\nlimit debate at any time.\nSouthern Democrats branded\nthis as a* move to choke off fili\nbusters and put over President\nTruman's civil rights program.\nThey have tied the Senate up with\ntalk for most of two days.\nSenator Lucas said he will move\ntomorrow to file a cloture petition\nto limit debate. Then it will be\nup to Vice President Barkley to\ndecide whether to follow Senator\nVandenberg's precedent and throw\nj the petition out or whether to hold\nthat a debate gag can be applied\nnow.\nMost Senators are betting that\nMr. Barkley will reverse the Van\ndenberg ruling.\nIf he does, the Southerners\nwill appeal to the Senate. Sena\ntor Lucas then can force a vote\non the appeal at a convenient\ntime.\nSenator Vandenberg is expect\ned to argue in the Senate that no\nmatter how a Senator feels about\nthe civil rights program, the Sen\nate\u2019s rules ought to be changed\nby the passage of a resolution\u2014\nand not by a decision of the pre\nsiding officer.\nRepublicans to Meet Today.\nSenator Wherry, who argues the\nsame way, wouldn\u2019t say whether\nhe will vote for or against a rul\ning by Mr. Barkley that cloture\ncan be applied to debate on a\nmotion to take up a rule or bill\u2014\nthe present situation in the Sen\nate.\nSenator Wherry said that \u201cquite\na few\u201d Republicans probably will\nvote against any Barkley ruling\nfor an immediate debate limita\ntion. Twenty Southerners and\nsome other Democrats will be\nagainst it, so the outcome may be\nextremely close.\nChairman Taft of the Senate\nj (See FILJBUSTERTPage A-6.)\u201c\nReds Join Karen Rebels\nIn Attack on Mandalay\nRANGOON, Burma, Mar. 2. (A\u2019)\n\u2014Communists haVe joined Karen\nrebels in an attack on Mandalay,\nit was announced today.\nA communique said the attackers\nhad taken up new positions below\nthe river where they are running\ninto government resistance.\nThe statement said Karen\nsnipers inside Mytinge were being\nwiped out.\n56 Guerrillas Killed\nIn Battle, Greece Says\nBy tht Associated Pres*\nATHENS, Mar. 2.\u2014The Greek\ngeneral staff reported today 56\nguerrillas were killed and 32 were\ncaptured in a running battle\nnorth of Karpenissi.\nThe communique reported the\nguerrilla casualties were in addi\ntion to the capture of 210 an\nnounced yesterday.\nA high military source said the\nguerrillas have lost more than\n1,000 killed or captured since they\nwere driven out of Karpenissi,\nFebruary 7. Karpenissi is 125\nmiles northwest of Athens.\nAxis Sally Completes\nTestimony, Refuses to\nAnswer Prosecutor\nKelley Drop's Attempt to\nForce New Details on\nLife With Nazi Professor\nBy James J. Cullinane\nAfter successfully defying Gov\nernment attempts to delve deeper\ninto her life, Mildred E. (Axis\nSally) Gillars today completed the\ntestimony on which she bases her\ndefense against charges of treason.\nPale, but calm, Miss Gillars\nfirmly refused to answer questions\nabout her romances propounded\nby Chief Prosecutor John M. Kel\nley, jr. When Judge Edward M.\nCurran directed her to answer,\nshe threw back her chin and\nasked:\n\"And what happens if I refuse?\u201d\nJudge Curran looked at the\nsmall 48-year-old woman and\nsaid:\n\"You must answer the question.\u201d\nKelley Avoids Showdown.\nMr. Kelley avoided a showdown\nby withdrawing his question, in\ntended to force Miss Gillars to\nexplain what happened soon after\nthe war ended when she met Miss\nStella Koischwitz. teen-aged\ndaughter of the late Prof. Otto\nKoischwitz, the man she loved.\nSoon after Miss Gillars returned\nto the stand this morning, Mr.\nKelley began going into her re\nlationship with Koischwitz, who\nleft his post at Hunter College in\nNew York in 1939 to become an\ninfluential figure in the Nazi gov\nernment and a confidente of Nazi\nForeign Minister von Ribbentrop.\nMiss Gillars had testified previ\nously that Koischwitz had declared\nhis love for her in the spring of\n1943.\nIsn't it a fact,\" demanded the1\nprosecutor, \u2018\u2018that when you and\nProf. Koischwitz declared your\nlove for each other his wife was\npregnant and bearing his fourth\nchild?\u201d\n\u2018\u2018I found out about it the day\nbefore the child was born,\u201d Miss\nGillars responded.\nSally Chides Prosecutor.\n\"You knew he was married?\"\n\u2018\u2018Mr. Kelley,\u201d Miss Gillars re\nsponded angrily, \u201care these ad\nhominum (Latin for directly per\nsonal* tactics going to be pur\nsued\u2014is that the only kind of\nattack you have, Mr. Kelley?\u201d\nMr. Kelley asked Judge Curran\nto instruct the witness that she\nmust answer his questions. Miss\nGillars then responded affirma\ntively.\nA short time later, however,\nwhen Mr. Kelley was attempting\nto show that Koischwitz's daugh\nter held resentment against Miss\nGillars, the witness bristled and\nbecame adamant.\nMr. Kelley asked Miss Gillars if\nStella Koischwitz had ordered her\nout of the professor's apartment\n(Continued on Page A-6, Col. 1.)\nGreece Dooms Five Reds\nATHENS, Mar. 2 A Greek\nmilitary court today sentenced five\nCommunists to death on charges\nof sabotage. Three of the doomed\npersons are women.\nBusiness Still Good,\nTruman Informed by\nEconomic Advisers\nNight Conferences With\nIndustrial Leaders at\nBlair House Disclosed\nPresident Truman today re\nceived from his economic advisers\na report that \u201cbusiness conditions\nare still very good\u201d and the out\nlook \u201cpromising\u201d as the White\nHouse disclosed that Mr. Truman\nhas been holding a series of un\npublicized night conferences with\nbusiness leaders.\nThe estimate on the business\noutlook came from Leon Keyser\nI ling and John D. Clark of the\nPresident\u2019s Council of Economic\nAdvisers during a White House\ncall. Dr. Edwin C. Nourse, coun\ncil chairman, is out of the city.\nAfter seeing Mr. Truman, the\neconomists told reporters they had\nmade an oral report to the Pres\nident saying there had been little\neconomic change in the past\nmonth and that there was a de\ncline in the number of new claims\nfor unemployment compensation.\nRetail sales for January and Feb\nruary, they reported, are up to\nlevels of those two months of last\nyear and business investment plans\nappear to be good.\nSome Prices at Peak.\nMr. Keyserling reiterated that\nthe standby inflation controls,\nwhich the President has urged on\nCongress, still are needed. He\npointed out that the latest figures\nshow prices on metal, metal prod\nucts, fuels and lighting are at all\ntime highs, which, Mr. Keyserling\nsaid, demonstrates that \u201cin some\nareas there is still inflation.\u201d\nHe, in effect, repeated Dr.\nNourse's recent warning to the\npublic about not getting \u201cjittery.\u201d\ndeclaring we must keep the people\nI from getting a distorted phycho\nlogical fear of the situation.\nIn the meantime, Eben Ayers,\nassistant press secretary, told re\nporters the President was having\n'night conferences with industrial\n(See ECONOMIC, Page A-6.)\nFrench Refuse to Invite\nTruman, Stalin to Talk\nBy the Associated Press\nPARIS. Mar. 2.\u2014The Foreign\nAffairs Committee of the French\nNational Assembly rejected today\na proposal to invite President\nTruman and Prime Minister Stalin\nto confer in Paris.\nA substitute measure was\nadopted. It woud invite \u201call in\nterested countries\u201d to send repre\nsentatives here for \u201ca major effort\nfor peace.\u201d The measure now goes\nto the National Assembly for\napproval. _\nRankin Seeks to Clear\nVeterans' Pension Bill\nFor Action on Floor\nEstimates Over-All Cost\nOf Program Will Reach\n100 to 103 Billions\nRepresentative Rankin, Demo\ncrat, of Mississippi, today ap\npealed to the House Rules Com\nmittee to send to the -floor his bill\ncalling for pensions of $90 a\nmonth for veterans of World War\nI and II.\nMr. Rankin, chairman of the\nHouse Veterans Committee, asked\nfor a closed rule which would per\nmit only committee amendments.\nBut he added that he would accent\nan open rule allowing free amend\nments from the floor.\nSaying the bill would relieve\nStates of a substantial portion of\ntheir old-age assistance costs, Mr.\nRankin estimated the total cost\nof the pension plan would be\n$100,000,000,000 to $103,000,000,\n000. He said the cost would rise\nfrom $62,000,000 the first year to a\npeak of $4,446,000,000 in 41,years.\nMay Not Decide Today.\nAlthough such hearings before\nthe Rules Committee usually are\nbrief, a decision on sending the\nmeasure, which lacks administra\ntion backing, to the House may\nnot be reached during the day.\nChairman Sabath of the commit\ntee said all* members of Congress\nwho want to testify will be heard\non the proposal.\nMr. Rankin said the measure\nhas the support of the American\nLegion and was not opposed by\nthe Veterans of Foreign Wars. He\nadded that it had been hampered\nby \"a mass of misinformation\" in\nthe press and on the radio about\nthe attitude of veterans toward it.\nMay Try to Delay Bill.\nIn advance of the hearing, Rep\nresentative Patten, Democrat, of\nI Arizona said some members of the\nVeterans\u2019 Committee might try to\nget the bill sent back to that group\nfor further study.\n\u201cThe bill was improperly re\npoited out, and without adequate\nhearings,\u201d he said.\nMr. Patten, together with five\nother Democratic members of the\ncommittee and one Republican,\nwalked out during consideration\nof the bill, accusing Chairman\nRankin of jamming through a\nmeasure they had not had time\nto study.\nThree Killed in Cyclone\nBRISBANE, Australia, Mar. 2.\n(/P)\u2014A cyclone struck the Queens\nland cost today, killing three per\nsons and injuring a number of\nothers. More than 300 persons\nwere homeless at Gladstone, 320\nmiles north of Brisbane.\n_A\nPilot of World-Girdling Plane\nSays You Can Fly Anywhere\nBy the Associated Press\nFORT WORTH, Tex., Mar. 2.\u2014\nSaid the chief pilot of the first\nplane to circle the earth without\nstopping:\n\u201cIt just means you can fly any\nwhere any time.\u201d\nCapt. James Gallagher of Mel\nrose, Minn., commander and pilot\nof the Lucky Lady II. gathered\nwith his men in the Carswell Air\nBase briefing room today a few\nminutes after they ended their\nhistoric flight.\nGenerals and colonels served\nhot coffee to the tired, happy\nflyers.\nCapt. Gallagher summed up the\nflight in answer to questions by\nnewsmen.\nAsked if he would want to take\nanother world trip immediately,\nCapt. Gallagher laughed and the\ncrew joined in.\n\u201cJust give us a little rest and\nwe\u2019ll be all right,\u201d the flight com-1\nimander said.\nHe said the crew, which worked\nin shifts, slept well in its off hours.\nBut a sleepy-eyed Texas ser\ngeant with a stubble of beard\nsaid: \u201cI'm tired. I want some\nsleep.\u201d\nHe was S Sergt. Robert R.\nMcLeroy, 26, of Alvarado.\nSergt. McLeroy blinked his eyes\nand scratched the back of his\nhead as he lined up with other\ncrewmen for pictures.\nGrinning tiredly, he said, \u201cI feel\nfine and got a little sleep every\nonce in a while. Everything went\noff smooth.\u201d\nHe has been in the Air Force\neight years.\nThe dead-tired airmen lined up\nunder the silver nose of the plane.\nThere they were congratulated by\nAir Secretary Symington, Gen.\nCurtis, Le May, head of the Stra\ntegic Air Command; Gen. Roger\nRamey, commander of the 8th Air\nForce; Gen. Hoyt Vandenberg, Air\nForce chief of staff, and others.\nB-29 Tankers1\nUsed to Provide\nGas Supply\nBy John A. Giles\nStar Staff Correspondent\nFORT WORTH, Tex., Mar 2.\u2014\nThe first non-stop flight around\nthe world was completed here\nthis morning in less than four\ndays by a new Boeing B-50 Super\nfortress which refueled four times\nin the air.\nThe swift, high-powered suc\ncessor to the war-famed B-29\nrolled to a halt on Carswell Air\nForce Base at 10:36 a.m. <EST)\nbefore an assemblage of ranking\nofficers headed by Air Secretary\nSymington.\nCommanded by Capt. James\nGallagher of Melrose, Minn., and\noperated by 13 other officers and\nenlisted men, the \u201cLucky Lady II\u201d\nhad taken on fuel over the Azores,\nSaudi Arabia, the Philippines and\nHawaii while forging steadily east\nward on a 23,452-mile course,\nj The big bomber used a technique\ni developed since the war for refuel\niing in flight from \u201cmother\u201d tankers\n2 Faster World Flights\nTook Shorter Routes\nAnd Made Stops\nThe 94 hours and 1 minute\nelapsed time of the \u201cLucky\nLady II\u201d was slower than two\nother world flights, but the\ncourses of those were shorter\nthan the 23,452 miles flown by\nthe B-50.\nIn 1947 William Odom, ac\ncompanied by Milton Reyn\nolds, flew a converted Air\nPorce medium bomber over\n20,000 miles around the world\nin an elapsed time of 76 hours\nand 55 minutes.\nHoward Hughes, airplane\ndesigner, made a much short\ner flight on a more northerly\ncourse. He was able to pass\nthrough Russia on the trip in\n1938 and covered 14,824 miles\nin 91 hours and 8 minutes.\nThe late Wiley Post made\ntwo trips. His best time was\nin 1933, when he covered 15,\n000 miles in 186 hours and\n49! 2 minutes.\nto extend the range of the planes.\nAn unannounced number of B-50S\nand B-29s they are replacing have\nbeen modified at the Boeing plant\nin Wichita for refueling.\nB-29s Used as Tankers.\n1 The \u201cLucky Lady II\u201d had de\nparted from Carswell Field at\n12:21 p.m. (EST) Saturday. Rated\nin the 300 to 400-mile-an-hour\nclass, the bomber was routed east\nward to take advantage of prevail\ning easterly winds north of the\nEquator. Economy cruising speed\nwas far under the maximum^\nAt each of the refueling bases\nfour or five B-29 tankers had\nassembled, although only two were\nused at each rendezvous point.\nThe first refueling point at the\nAzores was 3,800 miles from Cars\ni well Field, the next jump to\nDhahran in Saudi Arabia was\n5,200 miles and the third was 4,900\n[miles to the Philippines.\nI The longest jump was about\n5,300 miles from the Philippines\nto Hawaii, where enough gas was\ntaken aboard to carry the big\nbomber 3,700 miles to home base.\nElapsed Time 94 Hours.\nUnofficial elapsed time for the\nglobe-girdling voyage was 94 hours\nand 1 minute. An average speed\nof 250 miles an hour was main\ntained.\nSecretary of Defense Forrestal\nsent immediate congratulations to\nthe Air Force on the flight.\nIn a telegram from Washington\nto Secretary Symington and Gen.\nHoyt S. Vandenberg, Air Force\nchief of staff here, Mr. Forrestal\nsaid:\n\u201cThe completion of the first\naround-the-world non-stop flight\nis a significant achievement.\n(Through you I send my sincere\n[congratulations to the Air Force\n(Continued on Page A-3, Col. 2.)\nSenate Unit Urges Detroit\nFor 1956 Olympic Games\nBy tht Associated Press\nThe Senate Foreign Relations\nCommittee today approved a reso\nlution urging that the 1956 Olym\npic Games be held in Detroit.\nChairman Connally said he be\nlieves the Senate will act favorably\non the resolution.\nHe said the Olympics Associa\ntion had agreed the games should\nbe held in Detroit.\nThe last Olympic Games held\nin the United States were in 1932\nat Los Angeles.\nSenator Connally said it was un\nderstood that Detroit would not\ncall on the Government for any\nfunds in helping stage the game*.","height":"31960","width":"22612"}}
